    <segment id="1" parent="16" relname="span">Error recovery is an important attribute to consider .</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="19" relname="span">Preece,Sharp and Rogers said &quot;Interaction Design&quot; that we evaluate an interface to answers these questions:</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="17" relname="list"> -Are error messages helpful?</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="17" relname="list"> -Do they use plain language to describe the nature of the problem and suggest away of solving it?</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="15" relname="span"> Errors are bound to occur</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="5" relname="volitional-result"> and users aren&apos;talways experts with some interface and need to be able to recover from errors as painlessly as possible.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="13" relname="span"> Also,efficiency refers to the way a system supports users in carrying out their tasks.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="12" relname="span">We have to always keep in mind that in auser centered design approach the taskd a user will carry out must be understood.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="8" relname="elaboration">We have to learn what taskd users will be trying to accomplish with the system.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="18" relname="span">Once we understand the requirements set by the users tasks</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="20" relname="span"> then we can make the interface efficient to accomplish these tasks.</segment>
